paragraphs.text:
%md
## Predicting Target Customers using Classification using Naive Bayes
In this notebook, we predict customers most likely to be positive responders to an Affinity Card loyalty program.

High Affinity Card responders (target value = 1) are defined as those customers who, when given a loyalty or affinity card, hyper-respond, that is, increase purchases more than the Affinity Card program's offered discount.

This notebook builds and applies a classification decision tree model using the Sales History (SH) schema data. All processing occurs inside Oracle Autonomous Database.

paragraphs.title: Split into train and test sets
paragraphs.text:
%r

set.seed(123)
sampleSize <- .4 * nrow(DEMO_DF)
index <- sample(1:nrow(DEMO_DF),sampleSize)
group <- as.integer(1:nrow(DEMO_DF) %in% index)

# Create training data set
DEMO_DF.train <- DEMO_DF[group==FALSE,]

# Create test data set
DEMO_DF.test <- DEMO_DF[group==TRUE,]

%md
### Build a Naive Bayes model to predict AFFINITY_CARD
<hr>

msg.data: Build a Naive Bayes model to predict AFFINITY_CARD

paragraphs.title: Build a Naive Bayes Model using default settings
paragraphs.text:
%r

nb_mod <- ore.odmNB(AFFINITY_CARD ~., DEMO_DF.train)
summary(nb_mod)

paragraphs.title: Show model accuracy on data
paragraphs.text:
%r

nb_res <- predict(nb_mod, DEMO_DF.test, c('AFFINITY_CARD', "CUST_ID"))

confusion_matrix <- with(nb_res, table(AFFINITY_CARD, PREDICTION))
names(dimnames(confusion_matrix)) <- c("ACTUAL","PREDICTED")
confusion_matrix

accuracy <- confusion_matrix/sum(confusion_matrix)
cat("\nAccuracy:") 
round(sum(diag(accuracy)),4)

paragraphs.title: Examples of possible setting overrides for NB
paragraphs.text: %md ### Examples of possible setting overrides for Naive Bayes If the user does not override the default settings, then relevant settings are determined by the algorithm A complete list of settings can be found in the Documentation link: – Algorithm Settings: Naive Bayes – Shared Settings: All algorithms – Enable Sampling, this allows the use to request sampling of the build data ``` ODMS_SAMPLING = 'ODMS_SAMPLING_DISABLE' ``` – Specify the value of pairwise threshold for the Naive Bayes algorithm The value required is between 0 and 1 (including the edges), and the default value is 0. ``` NABS_PAIRWISE_THRESHOLD = 0 ``` – Specify the value of a singleton threshold for the NB algorithm The value required is between 0 and 1 (including the edges), and the default value is 0. ``` NABS_SINGLETON_THRESHOLD = 0 ```

Examples of possible setting overrides for Naive Bayes

If the user does not override the default settings, then relevant settings are determined by the algorithm

A complete list of settings can be found in the Documentation link:

– Algorithm Settings: Naive Bayes

– Shared Settings: All algorithms

– Enable Sampling, this allows the use to request sampling of the build data

ODMS_SAMPLING = 'ODMS_SAMPLING_DISABLE'

– Specify the value of pairwise threshold for the Naive Bayes algorithm
The value required is between 0 and 1 (including the edges), and the default value is 0.

NABS_PAIRWISE_THRESHOLD = 0

– Specify the value of a singleton threshold for the NB algorithm
The value required is between 0 and 1 (including the edges), and the default value is 0.

NABS_SINGLETON_THRESHOLD = 0

paragraphs.title: Build a Naive Bayes Model using explicit settings
paragraphs.text:
%r

settings <- list(NABS_PAIRWISE_THRESHOLD = 0, NABS_SINGLETON_THRESHOLD = 0)
nb_mod2 <- ore.odmNB(AFFINITY_CARD ~., DEMO_DF.train, odm.settings = settings)
summary(nb_mod2)

paragraphs.title: Show model accuracy on data
paragraphs.text:
%r

nb_res <- predict(nb_mod2, DEMO_DF.test, c('AFFINITY_CARD', "CUST_ID"))
confusion_matrix <- with(nb_res, table(AFFINITY_CARD, PREDICTION))
colnames(nb_res) <- c( 'PROBABILITY_OF_0', 'PROBABILITY_OF_1', 'AFFINITY_CARD', 'CUST_ID' ,'PREDICTION')
df <- ore.push(nb_res)



accuracy <- confusion_matrix/sum(confusion_matrix)
cat("\nAccuracy:") 
round(sum(diag(accuracy)),4)

paragraphs.title: Display confusion matrix, lift chart and ROS curve
paragraphs.text:
%r

df <- ore.pull(df)
options(warn = -1)

confusion_matrix <- with(nb_res, table(AFFINITY_CARD, PREDICTION))
names(dimnames(confusion_matrix)) <- c("ACTUAL","PREDICTED")
confusion_matrix

# BAR PLOT
sensitivity <-df[order(df$PROBABILITY_OF_1, decreasing = TRUE),]
sens <- (sum(sensitivity$PROBABILITY_OF_0)/sum(sensitivity$PROBABILITY_OF_0) - cumsum(sensitivity$PROBABILITY_OF_0)/sum(sensitivity$PROBABILITY_OF_0))
spec <- cumsum(sensitivity$PROBABILITY_OF_1)/sum(sensitivity$PROBABILITY_OF_1)
# LIFT CHART
sensitivity2 <- df[order(df$PROBABILITY_OF_1,decreasing = TRUE), ]
decile <- quantile(sensitivity2$PROBABILITY_OF_1, probs = seq(.1, .9, by = .1))
df_sens <- as.data.frame(sensitivity2$PROBABILITY_OF_1, col.names = c('sens'))
df_sens$decile = as.numeric(cut(1-cumsum(df_sens$sens), breaks=10))
# DISTRIBUTION CHART
dx <- density(df$PROBABILITY_OF_0)
dx2 <- density(df$PROBABILITY_OF_1)
#PLOTS
par(mfrow=c(3,3))
plot(1 - spec, sens, type = 'l', col = 'darkred', ylab = 'Sensitivity', xlab = '1 - Specificity', main = 'ROC Curve')
abline(c(0,0),c(1,1))
paste('AUC: ', round(auc <- sum(spec*diff(c(0, 1 - sens))),3))
barplot(table(df_sens$decile), xlab = 'Decile', ylab = 'Actual Targets', main = 'Lift Chart', col='darkred')
plot(dx, lwd = 1, col = 'red', main = 'Density')
lines(dx2, lwd = 1, col = 'blue')
rug(jitter(df$PROBABILITY_OF_0),col='darkred')
rug(jitter(df$PROBABILITY_OF_1),col='blue')

paragraphs.title: Create named model to be used in SQL interface
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.exec("BEGIN DBMS_DATA_MINING.DROP_MODEL(model_name=> 'NB_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL'); EXCEPTION WHEN others THEN null; END;")

mod <- ore.odmNB(formula = AFFINITY_CARD ~ ., data = DEMO_DF.train, odm.settings = list(model_name = "NB_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL"))

paragraphs.title: Demonstrate using the SQL interface to score data and display prediction details
paragraphs.text:
%sql

SELECT CUST_ID,
       round(PREDICTION_AFFINITY_CARD,3) PREDICTION_AFFINITY_CARD,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute1",17,100)),'rank="1"/>') FIRST_ATTRIBUTE,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute2",17,100)),'rank="2"/>') SECOND_ATTRIBUTE,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute3",17,100)),'rank="3"/>') THIRD_ATTRIBUTE
FROM (SELECT CUST_ID,
             PREDICTION(NB_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL USING *) PREDICTION_AFFINITY_CARD,
             PREDICTION_DETAILS(NB_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL USING *) PD
      FROM DEMO_DF_NB
      WHERE CUST_ID < 100015
      ORDER BY CUST_ID) OUT,
          XMLTABLE('/Details'
                   PASSING OUT.PD
                   COLUMNS
                     "Attribute1" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[1]',
                     "Attribute2" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[2]',
                     "Attribute3" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[3]')
OUTPRED
